<p>Strings and Numbers are understood differently when read by the computer in the same way we understand Birds and Fish to be nouns that have type-specific ways of understanding them. Birds donâ€™t fly by flapping their fins for instance.</p>

<p>There are actions that each noun can inherently do because of their type. Letâ€™s look at Birds and Fish. Birds have available to them the action â€œfly,â€ and Fish has the action â€œswim.â€ In English, actions are called â€œverbs.â€ Some verbs are inherent to the type of creature. Fish donâ€™t have the action â€œflyâ€ available to them, but birds do (except adorable penguins and kiwis). In JavaScript, verbs are called methods. Usually, youâ€™ll know itâ€™s a method if it is attached to the noun with a <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">.</code> and is followed by <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">()</code>. Something like <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">String.trim()</code> is how the String calls the method â€œtrimâ€ to remove whitespace from the front and end of the String.</p>

<p>Adjectives in English befuddled me until junior high. I kept getting them confused with adverbs. Adjectives are words that describe the noun. JavaScript properties describe the object. <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">String.length</code> is used to describe a String by how many characters itâ€™s made of. So I could say to a person, â€œTell me, what color is the fish?â€ They would reply, â€œblue.â€ Likewise, we could ask a computer <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Fish.color</code> and receive the response <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">"blue"</code>.</p>

<h2 id="sentences-and-code-arent-just-strings-of-words">Sentences and code arenâ€™t just strings of words</h2>
<p>When we write a sentence in English, weâ€™re supposed to have a subject and predicate. A noun and verb. Same as in coding. â€œFishâ€ as a sentence means little and is pretty ambiguous. What about the fish? Are you telling someone to go fishing? Do you want a fish? â€œYou, give me a fish,â€ is clear and has a subject (you) and predicate (give). I could write that as <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">you.give(fish)</code> in JavaScript.</p>

